node.text:
Based on a threat-informed, ten-year time horizon, the Marine Corps is designing a force for naval expeditionary warfare in actively contested spaces. Throughout this ten-year initiative, the Marine Corps will make investments in capabilities to include long range precision fires, advanced reconnaissance capabilities, unmanned systems, and resilient networks. (U.S. Marine Corps video by Cpl. Nicholas Filca)

For more information, view the link in the bio.

node.text:
Colonel Dave E. Severance, who played a key role in the raising of the U.S. flag during the Battle of Iwo Jima, passed away at his home in California on 2 August, 2021, at the age 102. 

As the commander of Easy Company, 28th Marine Regiment, 5th Marine Division, it was then-Captain Severance’s Marines who summited Mount Suribachi on 23 February, 1945 and raised the U.S. flag famously photographed by Joe Rosenthal of the Associated Press. Col. Severance was personally awarded the Silver Star for subsequent actions on Iwo Jima after he “skillfully directed the assault on this strong enemy position despite stubborn resistance.” Col. Severance served in the Marine Corps until his retirement in 1968.

On the occasion of Col. Severance’s 100th birthday in 2019, the Commandant of the Marine Corps General Robert B. Neller sent Col. Severance a letter, recognizing him for his service and remarking that “from commanding the company that claimed the summit of Mt. Suribachi on Iwo Jima to flying combat missions in Korea, you played a crucial role in shaping the warrior ethos of our Corps. Marines in uniform today are proud to follow in your footsteps.” 

In addition to his courageous heroism, Col. Severance is remembered for his wit and humor – in a 2019 interview with the La Jolla Light, he was asked how he wished to be remembered. “I never thought about it,” said Col. Severance. “Just that I was a Marine for 30 years, and I never ended up in jail.”

Today, we pause to remember Col. Severance and the other Marines whose efforts to raise our nation’s flag on Iwo Jima that day stand so prominently in the memory of our Corps:

Cpl Harlon Block, KIA 
Pfc. Harold Keller
Pfc. Franklin Sousey, KIA
Sgt. Michael Strank, KIA
Pfc. Harold Schultz
Pfc. Ira Hayes

Lance Cpl. Alex Oley, a field radio operator with @iimefmarines conducts a radio check during Exercise Cyber Fury 21, at @camp.lejeune.
